 and artistic strategies for improvisatory living and gathering. Potentiating non-exclusionary belonging, black religion is anarchic, mystical, and experimental: it reveals alternative relationalities and visions of matter that can counter capitalism’s extractive, individualistic, and imperialist ideology. By enacting a black study of religion, Carter elucidates the violence of religion as the violence of modern life while also opening an alternate praxis of the sacred.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEvangelicalismxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aPolitical culturexHistoryy21st centuryzUnited States. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aRacexReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aRacism against Black peoplezUnited States. 0aRacismxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aReligion and politicsxHistoryy21st centuryzUnited States. 0aReligion and politicszUnited StatesxHistoryy21st century. 0aWhite supremacy movementsxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Black Studies (Global).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311099775008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishz978311131926108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023z9783111318806oZDB-23-DSL40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478027027?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478027027423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478027027/original  a978-3-11-099775-0  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b